text=(:if [ authgroup @tas || authgroup @admins || equal {$Author} '' ]:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=edit|Edit this page]] \\%0aStatus: {GradebookArticles.{$Name}$:Status} %0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!{$:Category}]]%0a%0a!Ute endangerment and revitalization%0a%0a:Author: dani26%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aEnglish appeals heavily to the Ute youth, resulting in less of them learning the language. Efforts to document the language with a dictionary are ongoing, as are projects to teach it to children.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThe Utes are a tribe residing in Utah and Colorado that speak the language named after their tribe (1). Its EGIDS level is currently endangered - "it is no longer the norm that children learn and use this language" (2).%0a%0aAmerican assimilation pressures like the convenience and appeal of English language media and the ageing of the fluent populaton are the main factors to the endangerment and continued decline of the Ute language (3).  With only about 3500 speakers remaining, most of them being quite elderly (1), there exists a serious possibility that there will not be many more children who have the family environment to acquire Ute as a first language and continue passing it down by the generations. The appeal and convenience of English stacks on top of the decreasing amount of familial support for learning the language, and understandably makes it difficult to pass down the language to many more generations. %0a%0aTo address the barriers of the ageing of the fluent population and the declining appeal to children for learning Ute, the tribe has been making an effort to team up with the local school districts to offer some instruction in Ute, modeled after a similar program for the Navajo language and culture; the Ute tribe's language coordinator also works hands-on with parents who have young children to teach the language to them so they may speak it fluently (3). There has also been (still!) ongoing work to create a dictionary for the language (4), which has been very successful thanks to a joint collaboration with tribal members, leadership, and academics, as well as The Language Conservancy. The website is modern, responsive, and represents a serious effort to use documentation as a driving force to preserving the language as it exists now, for use as a resource in the above efforts to ensure it passes on to more generations.%0a%0a----------%0a1: https://www.endangeredlanguages.com/lang/2965%0a2: https://www.ethnologue.com/size-and-vitality/ute%0a3: https://www.deseret.com/2007/4/22/20014405/utes-fear-their-language-could-disappear%0a4: https://dictionary.utelanguage.org/Acknowledgements%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%0aYou must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a%0a----%0a(:if equal {$Author} {$:Author}:)%0a!!Change article category%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#changearticlecategory:)%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a%0a(:Section: F:)%0a(:Category: EndangeredLanguages:)%0a(:Title: Ute endangerment and revitalization:)
